# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-application-insights
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:azure-application-insights/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] In computer programming, **instrumentation** is the act of modifying software so that analysis can be performed on it.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] Generally, instrumentation either modifies source code or binary code.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] Execution environments like the JVM provide separate interfaces to add instrumentation to program executions, such as the JVMTI, which enables instrumentation during program start.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] Instrumentation enables profiling: measuring dynamic behavior during a test run.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] This is useful for properties of a program that cannot be analyzed statically with sufficient precision, such as performance and alias analysis.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] Instrumentation is limited by execution coverage.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] If the program never reaches a particular point of execution, then instrumentation at that point collects no data.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] For instance, if a word processor application is instrumented, but the user never activates the print feature, then the instrumentation can say nothing about the routines which are used exclusively by the printing feature.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] Instrumentation increases the execution time of a program.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] In some contexts, this increase might be dramatic and hence limit the application of instrumentation to debugging contexts.
[src:azure-application-insights/instrumentation-computer-programming] The instrumentation overhead differs depending on the used instrumentation technology.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] In software engineering, **profiling** (**program profiling**, **software profiling**) is a form of dynamic program analysis that measures, for example, the space (memory) or time complexity of a program, the usage of particular instructions, or the frequency and duration of function calls.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Most commonly, profiling information serves to aid program optimization, and more specifically, performance engineering.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling is achieved by instrumenting either the program source code or its binary executable form using a tool called a *profiler* (or *code profiler*).
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers may use a number of different techniques, such as event-based, statistical, instrumented, and simulation methods.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers use a wide variety of techniques to collect data, including hardware interrupts, code instrumentation, instruction set simulation, operating system hooks, and performance counters.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Summary profile information is often shown annotated against the source code statements where the events occur, so the size of measurement data is linear to the code size of the program.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] For sequential programs, a summary profile is usually sufficient, but performance problems in parallel programs (waiting for messages or synchronization issues) often depend on the time relationship of events, thus requiring a full trace to get an understanding of what is happening.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] A trace may therefore be initiated at one point in a program and terminated at another point to limit the output.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] This provides the opportunity to switch a trace on or off at any desired point during execution in addition to viewing on-going metrics about the (still executing) program.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] It also provides the opportunity to suspend asynchronous processes at critical points to examine interactions with other parallel processes in more detail.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be applied to an individual method or at the scale of a module or program, to identify performance bottlenecks by making long-running code obvious.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be used to understand code from a timing point of view, with the objective of optimizing it to handle various runtime conditions or various loads.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be ingested by a compiler that provides profile-guided optimization.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be used to guide the design and optimization of an individual algorithm; the Krauss matching wildcards algorithm is an example.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers are built into some application performance management systems that aggregate profiling data to provide insight into transaction workloads in distributed applications.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Performance-analysis tools existed on IBM/360 and IBM/370 platforms from the early 1970s, usually based on timer interrupts which recorded the program status word (PSW) at set timer-intervals to detect "hot spots" in executing code.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] This was an early example of sampling (see below).
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] In early 1974 instruction-set simulators permitted full trace and other performance-monitoring features.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profiler-driven program analysis on Unix dates back to 1973, when Unix systems included a basic tool, `prof`, which listed each function and how much of program execution time it used.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] In 1982 `gprof` extended the concept to a complete call graph analysis.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] In 1994, Amitabh Srivastava and Alan Eustace of Digital Equipment Corporation published a paper describing ATOM (Analysis Tools with OM).
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] The ATOM platform converts a program into its own profiler: at compile time, it inserts code into the program to be analyzed.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] That inserted code outputs analysis data.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] This technique - modifying a program to analyze itself - is known as "instrumentation".
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] In 2004 both the `gprof` and ATOM papers appeared on the list of the 50 most influential PLDI papers for the 20-year period ending in 1999.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Flat profilers compute the average call times, from the calls, and do not break down the call times based on the callee or the context.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Call graph profilers show the call times, and frequencies of the functions, and also the call-chains involved based on the callee.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] In some tools full context is not preserved.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Input-sensitive profilers add a further dimension to flat or call-graph profilers by relating performance measures to features of the input workloads, such as input size or input values.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] They generate charts that characterize how an application's performance scales as a function of its input.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers, which are also programs themselves, analyze target programs by collecting information on the target program's execution.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Based on their data granularity, which depends upon how profilers collect information, they are classified as *event-based* or *statistical* profilers.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers interrupt program execution to collect information.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Those interrupts can limit time measurement resolution, which implies that timing results should be taken with a grain of salt.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Basic block profilers report a number of machine clock cycles devoted to executing each line of code, or timing based on adding those together; the timings reported per basic block may not reflect a difference between cache hits and misses.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] A sampling profiler probes the target program's call stack at regular intervals using operating system interrupts.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Sampling profiles are typically less numerically accurate and specific, providing only a statistical approximation, but allow the target program to run at near full speed.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] "The actual amount of error is usually more than one sampling period.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] In practice, sampling profilers can often provide a more accurate picture of the target program's execution than other approaches, as they are not as intrusive to the target program and thus don't have as many side effects (such as on memory caches or instruction decoding pipelines).
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Also since they don't create much overhead, they can detect issues that would otherwise be hidden.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] They are also relatively immune to over-evaluating the cost of small, frequently called routines or 'tight' loops.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] They can show the relative amount of time spent in user mode versus interruptible kernel mode such as system call processing.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Unfortunately, running kernel code to handle the interrupts incurs a minor loss of CPU cycles from the target program, diverts cache usage, and cannot distinguish the various tasks occurring in uninterruptible kernel code (microsecond-range activity) from user code.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Dedicated hardware can do better: ARM Cortex-M3 and some recent MIPS processors' JTAG interfaces have a PCSAMPLE register, which samples the program counter in a truly undetectable manner, allowing non-intrusive collection of a flat profile.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Some commonly used statistical profilers for Java/managed code are SmartBear Software's AQtime and Microsoft's CLR Profiler.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Those profilers also support native code profiling, along with Apple Inc.'s Shark (OSX), OProfile (Linux), Intel VTune and Parallel Amplifier (part of Intel Parallel Studio), and Oracle Performance Analyzer, among others.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] This technique effectively adds instructions to the target program to collect the required information.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Note that instrumenting a program can cause performance changes, and may in some cases lead to inaccurate results and/or heisenbugs.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] The effect will depend on what information is being collected, on the level of timing details reported, and on whether basic block profiling is used in conjunction with instrumentation.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] For example, adding code to count every procedure/routine call will probably have less effect than counting how many times each statement is obeyed.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] A few computers have special hardware to collect information; in this case the impact on the program is minimal.
[src:azure-application-insights/profiling-computer-programming] Instrumentation is key to determining the level of control and amount of time resolution available to the profilers.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] Software analytics aims at supporting decisions and generating insights, i.e., findings, conclusions, and evaluations about software systems and their implementation, composition, behavior, quality, evolution as well as about the activities of various stakeholders of these processes.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] Methods, techniques, and tools of software analytics typically rely on gathering, measuring, analyzing, and visualizing information found in the manifold data sources stored in software development environments and ecosystems.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] Core data sources include source code, "check-ins, work items, bug reports and test executions [...] recorded in software repositories such as CVS, Subversion, GIT, and Bugzilla." Telemetry data as well as execution traces or logs can also be taken into account.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] Automated analysis, massive data, and systematic reasoning support decision-making at almost all levels.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] In general, key technologies employed by software analytics include analytical technologies such as machine learning, data mining, statistics, pattern recognition, information visualization as well as large-scale data computing & processing.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] For example, software analytics tools allow users to map derived analysis results by means of software maps, which support interactively exploring system artifacts and correlated software metrics — such as class hierarchies and package coupling in a large Java application.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] There are also software analytics tools using analytical technologies on top of software quality models in agile software development companies, which support assessing software qualities (e.g., reliability), and deriving actions for their improvement.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] In 2009, the term "software analytics" was used in a paper by Dongmei Zhang, Shi Han, Yingnong Dang, Jian-Guang Lou, and Haidong Zhang in part by the Software Analytics Group (SA) at Microsoft Research Asia (MSRA).
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] In November 2010, Software Development Analytics (Software Analytics with a focus on Software Development) was proposed by Thomas Zimmermann and his colleagues at the Empirical Software Engineering Group (ESE) at Microsoft Research Redmond in their FoSER 2010 paper.
[src:azure-application-insights/software-analytics] A goldfish bowl panel on software development analytics was organized by Zimmermann and Tim Menzies from West Virginia University at the International Conference on Software Engineering, Software Engineering in Practice Track.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:azure-application-insights/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Logs that record program usage (such as a server log) or operating-system events primarily of interest to a system administrator (see for example *Event Viewer*) fall into a terminological gray area.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Tracing is primarily used for anomaly detection, fault analysis, debugging or diagnostic purposes in distributed software systems, such as microservices or serverless functions.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Software tracing is a tool for developers to gather information for debugging.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] This information is used both during development cycles and post-release.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Unlike event logging, software tracing usually does not have the concept of a "class" of event or an "event code".
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] OpenTelemetry is a CNCF open source project that provides comprehensive support for distributed tracing.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Some vendors including Datadog, Dynatrace, New Relic, Splunk also offer tracing SaaS services.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Google and Meta have developed their own tracing frameworks, named Dapper and Canopy respectively.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] In operating systems, tracing can be used in situations (such as booting) where some of the technologies used to provide event logging may not be available.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Linux offers system-level and user-level tracing capabilities with kernel markers and LTTng. ftrace also supports Linux kernel tracing. syslog is another tool in various operating systems for logging and tracing system messages.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] FreeBSD and SmartOS employ DTrace for tracing in both user space and kernel space.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] In embedded software, tracing also requires special techniques for efficient instrumentation and logging and low CPU overhead.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Trace generation of method calls can be done with source code instrumentation, runtime information collection, or under debugger control.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Tracing macros, aspect-oriented programming and related instrumentation techniques can be employed.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Libraries used in source code send data to an agent or directly to the collection component.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] To model execution trees, ISVis converts a rooted tree into a directed acyclic graph while Jinsight utilizes the call frame principle to gather and represent cumulative information about traces.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] The primary visualization method is the swimlane view, which is exemplified by tools like Jaeger and often includes annotations and key-value attributes.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Despite its widespread use, this design lacks rigorous justification and users frequently face challenges like missing features and confusing navigation.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Alternatives to swimlane views exist, like Jaeger’s service dependency view or SkyWalking’s List, Tree, and Table views.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Aggregate visualizations are also used for analyzing large volumes of traces, with systems like Canopy offering queryable metrics and Jaeger providing trace comparison features.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Event logging provides system administrators with information useful for diagnostics and auditing.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] The different classes of events that will be logged, as well as what details will appear in the event messages, are often considered early in the development cycle.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Many event logging technologies allow or even require each class of event to be assigned a unique "code", which is used by the event logging software or a separate viewer (e.g., Event Viewer) to format and output a human-readable message.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] This facilitates localization and allows system administrators to more easily obtain information on problems that occur.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Because event logging is used to log high-level information (often failure information), performance of the logging implementation is often less important.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] A special concern, preventing duplicate events from being recorded "too often" is taken care of through event throttling.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Difficulties in making a clear distinction between event logging and software tracing arise from the fact that some of the same technologies are used for both, and further because many of the criteria that distinguish between the two are continuous rather than discrete.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Enabling or disabling tracing during runtime often necessitates the inclusion of extra data in the binary.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] This can lead to performance degradation, even when tracing is not active.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] The overhead of tracing depends on the used framework and the activated features; in production servers, there is a trade-off between how fine-grained the tracing is and the incurred overhead.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] If tracing is enabled or disabled at compile-time, collecting trace data from a client's system hinges on their willingness and capability to install a version of the software specifically enabled for tracing, and subsequently replicate the issue.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Tracing in software typically demands high standards of robustness, not only in the accuracy and reliability of the trace output but also in ensuring that the process being traced remains uninterrupted.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] Given its low-level nature, tracing can generate a large volume of messages.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] To mitigate performance issues, it's often necessary to have the option to deactivate software tracing, either at the time of compilation or during run-time.
[src:azure-application-insights/tracing-software] In proprietary software, tracing data may include sensitive information about the product's source code.
